POETRY. I just want to write/create poetry for rest of my time. I would be good with that. No other kind of writing, at least not for me, is as freedom-having as shoveling an orange-blue sky and waiting for words to land like snowflakes at the tip of my tongue, and name it poem.

THIS is the moment my 15th and newest book, GROCERY SHOPPING WITH MY MOTHER, is officially on sale wherever books are sold online and offline. This is my first collection of poetry in 14 years, and I am humbled and grateful for the opportunity. I poured my spirit into these 36 poems, this book was inspired by my single mother’s illness a few years back. As an only child, as someone with a deep mother-son dynamic, I was terrified I might lose her, but I thank the universe daily she made it through, is still with us. I cannot fathom a world without my mother. But the experience pushed me into a role I was not prepared for emotionally, to look after my mother as she had once looked after me. I have posted to social media the past few years about our trips to the grocery store, our conversations, our adventures and misadventures, how challenging it has been for me to be my mother’s caretaker, about our very complicated relationship, about mental health and trauma. As I have always said, writing is as important to me as breathing, and writing, for me, is about truth, about making sense of chaos, it is about the art and craft of writing, yes, but also about healing, to me. GROCERY SHOPPING WITH MY MOTHER has grown to also be about me, you, us, all of us, about this world in which we live, as so much has happened in just the past few years, as you all know.  Finally, I take nothing for granted. I am a writer, have been since I was a kid, but my mom has a grade-school education, my grandmother, her ma, could not read or write, and I learned only recently my late father could not read or write either. I write for them, I write for me, I write for anyone who feels their voice does not matter. It does. It does. It does.

Exactly one year ago today, December 15th, we lost bell hooks. For me personally she was a long-time friend, mentor, teacher, sister. I got to see her in her native Kentucky, just days before her death. I wrote a poem called “letter to bell hooks” that you can read in my new poetry collection, GROCERY SHOPPING WITH MY MOTHER, or Google it in essence.com. I cry in the poem, I cried writing the poem, I cried when I saw bell in her final days. I think of bell often, wrote the poem to express my deep love and appreciation for her. This attached photo sheet by Eli Reed, from the 1990s, captures bell hooks perfectly. She was a genius, and she had mad jokes. bell hooks is gone, but she will never be forgotten.

RITA MORENO is one of the few artists/entertainers who has won an Oscar, an Emmy, a Tony, and a Grammy. Just watched the doc film about her life, RITA MORENO: JUST A GIRL WHO DECIDED TO GO FOR IT. This Puerto Rican sister is not just a legend, but what she has survived, my gosh. Racism, sexism, ugly and stereotypical roles that came her way, no one who looked like her on screen for many years, the brutal way actresses were treated long before the #MeToo movement exposed so much. And here she is in her 90s still standing, still acting, still fighting the good fight. So glad I watched this doc film. So many layers there just about life, about mental health, about following one’s passions in spite of all.

His name is King, he is 16, holding his copy of my new poetry book, GROCERY SHOPPING WITH MY MOTHER. Asking all of you who have the book to please take photo of you with it and tag me when you post photo to Twitter, LinkedIn, Instagram, or Facebook. This photo makes me so happy.

I AM HUMBLED AND PROUD AND EXCITED TO MAKE THIS ANNOUNCEMENT: My single mother, the first storyteller I ever knew, took me to the Greenville branch of the Jersey City Free Public Library when I was age 8 and it was there that I fell completely in love with words; and then: I’ve wanted to be a writer since age 11, got my first check as a professional writer at age 20, and for 30plus years I have written hundreds upon hundreds of articles, essays/blogs, profiles, speeches, and poems; I have interviewed everyday people, and leaders and influencers and artists of every kind, and the super famous; I’ve done many cover stories; I have been blessed to document huge chunks of the history of hip-hop as we celebrate its 50th birthday this year; I’ve done these things for more publications than I can remember, and now my 16th book is coming very soon, collecting a big sampling of my life work, as both a writer and an activist, into one space, including a couple of new and or previously unpublished pieces. It is called THE KEVIN POWELL READER: ESSENTIAL WRITINGS AND CONVERSATIONS, the publisher is Akashic Books, and it will be officially out on TUES, APR 4, 2023. The book cover, as designed by Hilary VanWright, is attached, and you can PRE-ORDER my newest book now, AT LINK IN BIO

Black history is American history 365 days of the year. Remove Black folks from history of America there are no inventions like traffic light, no rock and roll/jazz/hip-hop/blues/spirituals, no foods like okra and yams, and no constant convos on what word “democracy” should mean.

RECKONING is new book of collected writings by V, formerly Eve Ensler, creator of books, plays, V-Day movement, and “The Vagina Monologues.” I was at book launch last night. I remain BLOWN AWAY by passages of her book read. V is one of our great leaders/healers IN THE WORLD.

I have not listened to Sharon Jones and The Dap-Kings in a while and simply can’t get enough. Her voice IS Black History, IS Women’s History, is church fans and my momma and my auntie and their kitchen table summits. Rest forever in peace Ms. Jones, you are so missed.

Rest in peace Burt Bacharach, legendary songwriter, producer, pianist, more, whose songs were recorded by over 1000 different artists. His most famous collaborations were with Dionne Warwick, they are in attached photo together. The man won Grammys and Oscars for his life work.
Home plant life is a magical thing. They are alive, and so are the two other plants as well.

In honor of Burt Bacharach passing, I am playing the music of this multi-talented musical force today. He just died at 94 and I missed that he put out new music only two years ago, at age 92. I know many of his songs but the surprises are all the artists who recorded his songs.

One-hour spin class. I needed that. Very emotional day. Exercise is as much for our mental health as our physical health. Sometimes we just need to release situations, and release certain people’s energies too. #selfcare #healthiswealth

My Saturday morning music ahead of my yoga-meditation class is Dinah Washington, self-proclaimed “queen of the blues.” Fact is Dinah could sing in any genre, and did, and her voice needs to be acknowledged right up there with Ella and Sarah and other greats.

If I’ve learned nothing else in past 2-3 years this I have learned: ENERGY MATTERS. No friendship, or business, career, or job situation, or love relationship should continue for us if energy is way off, especially if writing was on wall at start. MY HAPPINESS IS NOT NEGOTIABLE.

I have now been practicing yoga and meditation since 2009, 14 years, and this form of exercise/deep stretching and breathing and slowing life down completely has been one of the best decisions of my entire life. Just in from a one-hour yoga-meditation session. I am so happy….

I’ve been a hip-hop head for life since before it was even officially called hip-hop.This culture, its four core elements—the deejay, the emcee (rapper), the dancer, the graffiti writer—all deep in me. So as we celebrate hip-hop at 50 this year I salute all those we’ve lost, too.

Much love and peace to you all on this Valentine’s Day. Some months ago I got married—my second marriage and her first—to the love of my life, my best friend, my soul mate, my everything. I love her in all ways, and am humbled and thrilled to spend rest of my life with her.
6am hour here in Texas, getting early morning workout in before a very long day. No excuses. Health is indeed wealth, helps the mental big time, and sets tone for the hours to come. Let’s get it.

My morning meditation/positive vibrations music is the great great great NAT “KING” COLE on shuffle. There are incredible singing voices and then there are voices that are one of the voices. That would be Mr. Cole. He did not even live long, just into early 40s. But what music.

Poetry is music and music is poetry, to me, and whether I listen to music when I am writing, or hearing dope or weird sounds in my head, no denying how necessary music is to my artist journey. That is why I decided to turn my most recent poetry collection, Grocery Shopping With My Mother, into my very first spoken word poetry album with music. In this 50th anniversary year of hip-hop—2023—I take it back to some of my early poetic inspirations, like Nikki Giovanni and Gil Scott-Heron;
but also remind myself, remind us all, that hip-hop culture owes a great debt to the recorded spoken word movement of the late 1960s and early 1970s. With these 9 poem-songs, as I call them, I marry the words with original music and original harmonies, while doing my best to stay true to the original material in my poetry book. Created over the course of eight months in 2023, I thought a lot about the music I have listened to since I was a child, be it the Motown sounds, the British Invasion, classic rock, spirituals, straight-ahead jazz, folk, pop, dance, rap, or reggae. I was determined to make an album as diverse as my musical tastes. I did, we did, I pray you like it. And simply no way I could have done it without the selfless genius that is my co-producer for the entire album, Tyneshia Hill, she/her, a supremely gifted singer, songwriter, and vocal arranger like few others. I gave Tyneshia my vision and she gave me the mighty push I needed from day one. And so this is not just my album, this is our album, from us to you.

—Kevin Powell, Brooklyn, New York

BE EXCELLENT OR BE MEDIOCRE. Excellence to me means not only doing your best, but forever open to growing, learning, doing things in new ways. Mediocrity is being good with way things are, resistant to new ideas, making peace with being average. BE EXCELLENT THIS WEEK, BEYOND.

Have not been feeling well. Sometimes just gotta hit a gym and sweat it out. Feel so much better but still barely have a voice. Lots of water and hot tea, and sleep.
The Beatles AND The Rolling Stones in 2023

I rarely ever get sick. I am a vegan, exercise almost daily, pray and meditate regularly, do therapy as often as I can, have spiritual practices I do my best to follow. But I got very sick this week because of work-related STRESS. I am not happy about that, the lessons are many. And self-care is mandatory.
PHILADELPHIA! Please note my event at African American Museum for WED NIGHT NOV 8 has been postponed until early 2024. More details coming soon.
Need to reset my day. It begins with album called ELLA FITZGERALD SINGS THE COLE PORTER SONGBOOK. Ella’s voice alone is healing, calming.

TODAY I was nominated for a Grammy for BEST SPOKEN WORD POETRY ALBUM. I am crying A LOT because of that, and because I got the news while visiting a dear friend who is dying. This Grammy nomination is for him. GROCERY SHOPPING WITH MY MOTHER is the name of my album. It is streaming EVERYWHERE. Pray for my friend, please.

#Grammy-nominated! I AM HUMBLED that my new record, GROCERY SHOPPING WITH MY MOTHER, has been nominated for 2024 #GRAMMY for Best Spoken Word Poetry Album. THANK YOU members of 
@RecordingAcademy. CONGRATULATIONS to my fellow nominees. POETRY at the #GRAMMYs!
HAPPY VETERANS DAY to all who have served, and are serving. Thank you for your service.

SIMPLY NO WAY I got this #Grammy nomination for Best Spoken Word Poetry Album alone. In soon-come posts I am going to acknowledge a lot of people—producers, musicians, singers, our sound engineer, others. I have honestly been overwhelmed by all the love. THANK YOU ALL SO MUCH.

My music to begin the week, Marvin Gaye’s spiritual and social justice classic, WHAT’S GOING ON. 52 years later and as timeless and timely as ever. “Save the children” Marvin sings in places. Save us all. Our world needs healing, and peace and love. Wishing you all a week of blessings. THINK OF THE CHILDREN, AND THE CHILDREN NOT YET BORN….

New Kevin Powell photo by Evangeline Lawson. She also shot the cover image for GROCERY SHOPPING WITH MY MOTHER, Kevin’s new poetry with music record, which is also now nominated for 2024 #GRAMMY for Best Spoken Word Poetry Album.

CARMEN MCRAE was one of our great jazz singers and interpreters of the human spirit who is not properly celebrated. Got her music on shuffle  tonight. You want to feel like a voice is singing only to you. Listen to some Carmen.
HEY EVERYONE! I will be on “The Karen Hunter Show” today, Sirius XM Urbanview Channel 126, 3pm-5pm New York City time. Can’t wait!

My wife and I were blessed to see X: THE LIFE AND TIMES OF MALCOLM X last night, the breath-taking opera about this man’s life, here in New York. In these times of so much confusion and hate, really something to see a piece like this fueled by a quest for justice, and Malcolm’s constant questioning and evolution. It was being filmed by The Metropolitan Opera, too, so my hope is many will see this opera one day.

social_posts.post_text: RADCLIFFE BAILEY, one of my longest, best friends, the great visual artist, is now with ancestors, may his soul rest, finally. I am thankful I got to see him in Atlanta days ago to say good-bye in person. I have cried, I could scream, this one HURTS. I love you Brother Radcliffe.

60 years ago today, November 22, 1963, President John F. Kennedy was lost to assassination, in broad daylight, in Dallas, Texas. A tragedy then, a tragedy still, given all the on-going confusion and theories over who and what and why. May his spirit continue to rest easy.

EVERYONE! Byron Hurt is one of the most visionary documentary filmmakers of this century.  His latest doc film, “Lee and Liza's Family Tree" PREMIERES TONIGHT  on NOVA PBS! It is a family-friendly story, and scientific journey of ancestral discovery. A MUST-WATCH!

I am THANKFUL every single day to God and my ancestors and my mother for life. I am THANKFUL to my dear wife for the incredible love and partnership and friendship. And I am THANKFUL to see each new day, to be able to help others, always, to be able to write, to be a witness.

New York City! CRAIG HARRIS is one of our musical griots! He is performing his jazz tribute to Muhammad Ali SUNDAY NIGHT, NOV 26, 7:30pm, at National Sawdust in Williamsburg section of Brooklyn. Please see attached flyer or please Google for all details.

HAPPY I was able to attend the celebration of life for my brother and friend RADCLIFFE BAILEY in Atlanta yesterday. It was a who’s who of ATL political leadership and the arts community.  Radcliffe was one of our GREAT visual artists, truly a national and global treasure. Please Google him, his work, his life. #RadcliffeForever

The past couple of months have brought much sadness and tears with losses of my first cousin Monique Powell-DeCicco Jones and my friend Radcliffe Bailey. She was only 51, him only 54. You think hard about your own life. I am more determined than ever to live free, and fully. But my God the grief is heavy. Waves of sadness often….

My music soundtrack this afternoon into evening is by John Coltrane. The 37 tracks compiled are called COLTRANE ‘58: THE PRESTIGE RECORDINGS. I cannot imagine life without the music and spirit of Coltrane in our home.

The music we digest on the regular can affect us in many ways, including what music we absorb to start and end our day. I love all kinds of music, I truly do, but have gravitated hard to jazz and classical and spirituals past few years, for my mental and my spiritual, honestly. This morning it is EXTENSIONS album from McCoy Tyner.

I have been going to therapy, for my mental health, off and on now for over 30 years, since I was very young. Just had a great and necessary session after a break of a couple of months. Being honest with self never easy, nor figuring out the healing paths, how to get there, always a work-in-progress. For me, therapy helps, in every way.
A gym, any decent gym, one of my safe and happy spaces. No one bothers you, folks doing their thing, and me doing mine.

HAPPY FOUNDERS’ DAY—December 4, 1906–to all my ALPHA PHI ALPHA FRATERNITY brothers worldwide. I am a proud Alpha brother because of men like W.E.B. DuBois, Paul Robeson, Thurgood Marshall, and the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. I stand on their shoulders. ‘00000006666!!!!
Got the daily workout done, ran the miles. Again, Happy Founders’ Day to all my Alpha Phi Alpha fraternity brothers across the globe. ‘06!
My music tonight is Frankie Lymon and The Teenagers, three African Americans and two Puerto Ricans, all teen boys from New York City, arguably the first boy band ever.

My Friday music, on shuffle, is that of Shirley Scott, hailed as the "Queen of the Organ" in her day. A Philadelphia native, Ms. Scott played every genre of music one could name, including various partnerships with her husband at the time, Stanley Turrentine, the jazz saxophonist.
Just got this JEAN-MICHEL BASQUIAT: KING PLEASURE book in the mail. I am one happy poet, let me tell you.
Spent part of today with three most important women in my life, my mother, my Aunt Cathy, and my wife.

social_posts.post_text: I am here in Alabama, up early, preparing to be the keynote speaker at a Dr. King breakfast. Took 9-10 hours to get here, being delayed at an airport, but my wife and I made it. My favorite singer and favorite song ever are Sam Cooke and his civil/human rights anthem, A CHANGE IS GONNA COME. It is playing in my head as I get ready. Thank you God for another day.
The Reverend Doctor Martin Luther King, Jr. was actually born on this day, January 15, in 1929, in Atlanta, Georgia. Happy birthday, Dr. King, and Happy MLK Day everyone!

My music today is MAYER HAWTHORNE. Honestly, I am mad late to game. My wife and I were in a store and I was like “Who is that doing such soulful music with modern touch?” She hipped me to him. Now I know. Listen….

THE KEVIN POWELL READER >>> As we continue to discuss and debate Dr. King, Black History, American Politics, Hip-hop, Education, and things like Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion, Akashic Books offers my 16th and newest book. It is my collected writings, interviews, poetry, and speeches, and more, covering 30plus years of politics and pop culture, including hip-hop. Get THE KEVIN POWELL READER wherever you buy books online, or at your local community bookstore. PLEASE ALSO NOTE the AUDIO BOOK version is READ BY ME and is available wherever you buy audio books online.
The great and everlasting SADE turned 65 this week, so her music is on shuffle for me today. Few artists have made truly timeless music. She is one of the few on entire planet.

Finally saw the film AMERICAN FICTION. Not just, to me, best film of 2023, but one  of the best films I have ever seen. Family, career, aging, mental health, race, and a main character who is a conflicted writer. SIMPLY BRILLIANT casting, directing, writing.

JONI MITCHELL landmark album called BLUE is my spiritual music and wake-up call this morning. I have long been a big fan of hers, her many works. But something deeply personal about this one that pulls me in, when I just need to be still, and quiet.

NINA SIMONE is my music this evening. Speak truth in all ways Miss Nina, speak truth. Few artists in music history have such a wide range of music plus a sharp social justice bent as her, like ever. Miss Nina could make any kind of music, and she did.
“Still Here” is a poem by LANGSTON HUGHES, my favorite writer ever. The poem is attached.
